summary: Anywhere You Want to Go by Undistinguishable Beat.  Crowley sat in dead silence, running his hands over the thermos of holy...
caption:
Anywhere You Want to Go by Undistinguishable Beat.

Crowley sat in dead silence, running his hands over the thermos of holy water. He had gotten what he wanted, but at what cost? “You go too fast for me, Crowley.” bounced around in his head like a sporadic ping pong ball, shattering his broken heart and twisting his thoughts. With a shaky breath, Crowley placed the holy water onto the passenger seat where his beautiful, hurt angel just sat, and turned on the radio.

With a collection of thoughts about one particular angel, this is what he heard while driving alone into the neon-darkness of night.

Song list: 

  • I’m a Fool to Want You by Chet Baker
  • Wild Is the Wind by Nina Simone
  • Angel Eyes by Ella Fitzgerald
  • Be Careful / It’s My Heart by Bing Crosby
  • I Fall in Love Too Easily by Chet Baker
  • Only Forever by Bing Crosby
  • It’s Always You by Frank Sinatra
  • Easy Living by Billie Holiday
  • If I Had You by Nat King Cole

summary: Rewatching the second episode and I love how indulgent and patient Crowley is with Aziraphale when he explains that it's a...
body: Rewatching the second episode and I love how indulgent and patient Crowley is with Aziraphale when he explains that it’s a paintball gun. Crowley absolutely, 100% knows what it is, but his angel is making a point to share his knowledge with Crowley and you can see not just the patience but kindness and love he has in the moment, nodding along without a lick of exasperation.

summary: I posted this a few days ago about Crowley and Aziraphale trying to teach Adam sex-ed (badly), and I’ve been thinking about it...
body:
I posted this a few days ago about Crowley and Aziraphale trying to teach Adam sex-ed (badly), and I’ve been thinking about it on and off since. Here are some of my ideas for how it might go down:

  • Anathema helps because someone has to
  • Zira does okay as long as he can stick to his pre-planned script and doesn’t have to answer any uncomfortable questions
  • Crowley initially feels kind of awkward but as things progress his own questions keep occuring to him
  • ‘So why put the prostate there anyway if the humans aren’t supposed to do that, then? Why make pregnancy so unpleasant? Why do STIs exist? What’s up with periods?’
  • ‘Yeah - what’s up with periods, Aziraphale?’ asks Anathema
  • Zira does not know and is regretting everything 
  • Crowley and Zira try to explain contraceptives but are only aware of methods that are centuries old, dodgy, and that they only heard of in passing, not exactly needing the stuff. Zira spends five entire minutes trying to remember if you’re supposed to eat the pomegranates before or after until Anathema finally interrupts
  • Of course, emotional health is another important aspect of The Talk
  • They explain that sometimes, you need to practise self care. Crowley informs Adam that if you’re sad, sleeping for a really long time is a good plan
  • ‘Don’t be ridiculous, dear’ says Zira, who then tells Adam that eating lots of sugary food is actually best practice
  • They both agree that getting very drunk is always a good solution though. Anathema kind of wants to cry
  • Finally, dating advice
  • Anathema: ‘If you like someone, try to make that clear, get to know them, see how it goes - hopefully it works out, but it’s best to move on if nothing seems to be going anywhere after, say, a month or so - much longer and it starts to get unhealthy’ 
  • Crowley: It’s best to what now

  • Of course, emotional health is another important aspect of The Talk
  • They explain that sometimes, you need to practise self care. Crowley informs Adam that if you’re sad, sleeping for a really long time is a good plan
  • ‘Don’t be ridiculous, dear’ says Zira, who then tells Adam that eating lots of sugary food is actually best practice
  • They both agree that getting very drunk is always a good solution though. Anathema kind of wants to cry
  • Finally, dating advice
  • Anathema: ‘If you like someone, try to make that clear, get to know them, see how it goes - hopefully it works out, but it’s best to move on if nothing seems to be going anywhere after, say, a month or so - much longer and it starts to get unhealthy’ 
  • Crowley: It’s best to what now
